<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1279,1446]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
The orange tortrix, 
<taxonomicName box="[367,652,1280,1304]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Argyrotaenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="franciscana">
<emphasis box="[367,652,1280,1304]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Argyrotaenia franciscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a polyphagous species that is an occasional pest of avocado in California. This species is found primarily in cooler coastal areas and river valleys, where adults may be present year round; only two generations are present in warmer inland areas (
<bibRefCitation author="Powell" box="[893,1041,1350,1374]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" refString="Powell, J. A. (1964) Biological and taxonomic studies on tortricine moths, with reference to the species in California. University of California Publications in Entomology. Vol. 32. 317 pp." type="book" year="1964">
Powell 
<number box="[981,1041,1350,1374]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" value="1964.0">1964</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae feed in silken shelters on outer shoots and can cause economic damage by chewing holes in fruit and even causing fruit to drop by feeding on the stem (
<bibRefCitation author="Faber" box="[259,456,1421,1446]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" refString="Faber, B. A., Morse, J. G. &amp; Hoddle, M. S. (2010) UC IPM Pest Management Guidelines - Avocado. University of California IPM Online. http: // www. ipm. ucdavis. edu / PMG / selectnewpest. avocado. html [Accessed 10 January 2011]." type="journal article" year="2010">
Faber 
<emphasis box="[332,388,1422,1446]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[395,456,1421,1445]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
